{"parse":{"title":"hen","pageid":39432,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"hen\"}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/hɛn/|a=RP,GA}}\n** {{audio|en|En-us-hen.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hɪn/|a=US,pin-pen}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hen/|a=AU,NZ}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛn|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n[[File:Mother hen with chicks02.jpg|thumb|A mother hen with [[chick]]s.]]\n\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*keh₂n-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|hen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|henn||hen}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hannju}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hanjō||hen}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*kan-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*kana-||to sing}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|stq|Hanne|t=hen}}, {{cog|fy|hin|t=hen}}, {{cog|nl|hen|t=hen}}, {{cog|nds-de|Heen|t=hen}}, {{cog|de|Henne|t=hen}}, {{cog|da|høne|t=hen}}, {{cog|sv|höna|t=hen}}, {{cog|is|hæna|t=hen}}. Related to {{cog|ang|hana|t=cock, rooster}}. Also cognate to {{cog|la|cicōnia||stork}}, {{cog|la|canō||to sing}}, {{cog|ru|каню́к||buzzard}}. Compare {{m+|ru|пету́х||rooster, cock}} from {{m+|ru|петь||to sing}}.\n\n{{senseno|en|woman's penis|uc=1}} after {{m|en|cock|t=male chicken; man's penis}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|en|henne}} {{q|obsolete}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q2201314}} A [[female]] [[chicken#English:_Q780|chicken]] ({{taxfmt|Gallus gallus|species}}), especially a [[sexually]] [[mature]] one kept for her [[egg]]s.\n#: {{hyper|en|chicken<id:Q780>|<|poultry<id:Q178559>}}\n#: {{hypo|en|pullet<id:young hen><!--sometimes construed as coordinate, when hen means mature hen specifically-->}}\n#: {{cot|en|cock<id:rooster>|cockerel|rooster}}\n#* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=2|passage=She was a fat, round little woman, richly apparelled in velvet and lace, {{...}}; and the way she laughed, cackling like a '''hen''', the way she talked to the waiters and the maid,{{nb...}}—all these unexpected phenomena impelled one to hysterical mirth, and made one class her with such immortally ludicrous types as Ally Sloper, the Widow Twankey, or Miss Moucher.}}\n# A [[female]] of other [[bird]] species, particularly a [[sexually]] [[mature]] female [[fowl]].\n#: {{cot|en|cock}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=17 June 2023|author=Severin Carrell|title=Dancing Capercaillie bird makes a tentative comeback in Scotland|journal=w:The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/jun/17/capercaillie-bird-tentative-comeback-scotland|text=In Tain, north of Inverness, staff detected 11 males and at least seven '''hens''' – the highest number there since 2011.}}\n# {{lb|en|uncommon}} A [[female]] [[fish]] (especially a [[salmon]] or [[trout]]) or [[crustacean]].\n#: {{syn|en|fishess<l:rare,chiefly,humorous>|henfish|spawner}}\n#: {{cot|en|buck|cock|cockfish}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2005|author=Roderick Sutterby; Malcolm Greenhalgh|chapter=Life in the Nursery|title=Atlantic Salmon: An Illustrated Natural History|location=Mechanicsburg, PA|publisher=Stackpole Books|isbn=9780811701457|page={{gbooks|HOEEZhSF4-gC|21|hen}}|passage=As spawning time approaches – autumn or very early winter in most rivers, though in some late-run streams salmon may spawn as late as January or February – the '''hen'''{{'}}s colouration becomes first a matt-pewter and then a drab dark brown-grey. The cock fish, in contrast, begins to gain some brighter colours.}}\n# {{lb|en|figuratively}} A [[woman]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1785|author=Francis Grose|title=A Classical Dictionary of the Vulgar Tongue\n|passage='''''Hen''''', a woman. A cock and '''hen''' club; a club composed of men and women.}}\n## {{lb|en|UK|informal}} A [[bride-to-be]], particularly in the [[context]] of a [[hen night]].\n# {{lb|en|UK|informal}} A [[hen night]].\n# {{lb|en|Scotland|informal}} {{n-g|An affectionate term of address used to women or girls.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Don't cry, '''hen'''. Everything will be all right.}}\n# {{senseid|en|woman's penis}} {{lb|en|transgender slang}} The [[penis]] of a [[trans woman]].\n#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:trans woman's penis}}\n#: {{coord|en|cock}}\n# {{lb|en|figuratively|pejorative|uncommon}} A [[henlike]] [[person]] of [[either]] [[sex]].\n# The [[hard clam]] ({{taxfmt|Mercenaria mercenaria|species}}), a [[bivalve]] [[shellfish]].\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A large [[pewter]] [[pot]] used in a [[tavern]].\n#: {{cot|en|chicken}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|female bird}} {{l|en|hen-bird}}\n* {{sense|bride-to-be}} {{l|en|bachelorette}} {{q|US}}\n* {{sense|M. mercenaria}} {{l|en|hard clam}}, {{l|en|hen-clam}}, {{l|en|hen-fish}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|blue hen|gorhen|hencoop|henfest|henhood|henhussy|henless|hennery|hennish|henny|henopause|henroost|henwife|henyard|mudhen|newshen|sagehen|waterhen\n|angry as a wet hen\n|battery hen\n|better an egg today than a hen tomorrow\n|blue hen-hawk|hen up\n|bush-hen\n|chaparral hen\n|cock and hen,cock-and-hen|hen clam\n|cock-and-hen club\n|Cornish game hen\n|Cornish hen\n|daker-hen\n|dakerhen\n|fat hen\n|grey hen,greyhen,gray hen\n|guinea hen|Maori hen|mud hen\n|guinea-hen\n|guinea hen weed|jungle hen\n|hazel hen\n|hazel-hen\n|heath hen\n|heath-hen\n|hen and chicken\n|hen and chicks\n|hen-and-egg\n|hen-balk\n|henbane\n|hen-blindness\n|hen-brained\n|hen-cackle\n|hen-clam\n|hen-corn\n|hen-court\n|hen-dam\n|hen do\n|hen dove\n|hen-dove\n|hen-driver\n|hen-feathered\n|hen-fish\n|hen-flesh\n|hen-footed\n|hen-frigate\n|hen-fruit\n|hen-harm\n|hen harrier\n|hen-harrier\n|hen-hawk\n|hen-headed\n|hen hearted\n|hen-hearted\n|hen-heartedness\n|henhouse\n|hen house\n|hen-house\n|hen-hutch\n|hen-keep\n|hen-killer\n|henlike\n|hen-like\n|hen-loft\n|hen louse\n|hen-mould\n|hen night\n|hen of grease\n|hen of Guinea\n|hen of the woods\n|hen party\n|hen-party\n|hen peck\n|hen-peck\n|henpeck\n|henpecked\n|hen pigeon\n|hen-pigeon\n|hen-plant\n|hen run\n|hen-run\n|henshit\n|hen's bill\n|hen-scratch\n|hen scratch\n|hen's fruit\n|hen's teeth\n|hens' teeth\n|hen's tooth\n|hensure\n|hensureness\n|hen-tailed\n|hen-toed\n|hen-trough\n|hen weekend\n|hen-wife\n|hen-witted\n|hen-yard\n|laying hen\n|like a hen on a hot griddle\n|like a hen with one chick\n|mad as a wet hen\n|mallee hen\n|marsh hen\n|miserable as a wet hen\n|moorhen\n|mother hen\n|mother-hen\n|Our Lady's hen\n|peahen\n|Pharaoh's hen\n|Port Egmont hen\n|rare as hen's teeth\n|rare as hens' teeth\n|rice hen\n|sage hen\n|scarce as hen's teeth\n|sea hen\n|sea-hen\n|spruce hen\n|stank hen\n|swamphen\n|tappit hen\n|turkey hen\n|turkey-hen\n|water hen\n|wild as a wet hen\n|woodhen\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|female chicken}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|hen}}\n* Aghwan: {{tt|xag|𐕄𐕒𐕡𐕄𐕒𐕡𐕟}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|pulë|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{tt|alt|така}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|دَجَاجَة|f}}, {{tt+|ar|دُجَاجَة|f}}, {{tt+|ar|دِجَاجَة|f}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|فَرْخَة|f|tr=farḵa}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{tt|acw|دُجاجة|f|tr=dujāja}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{tt|ary|دْجاجة|f|tr=djæja}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{tt|aii|ܟܬܲܝܬܵܐ|f|tr=ktayta}}, {{tt|aii|ܬܲܪܢܵܓܘܿܠܬܵܐ|f|tr=tāragolta}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|հավ}}\n* Aromanian: {{tt|rup|gãljinã|f}}\n* Assamese: {{tt|as|কুকুৰা}}\n* Asturian: {{tt+|ast|pita|f}}, {{tt+|ast|gallina|f}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|toyuq}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|тауыҡ}}\n* Basque: {{tt|eu|oilo}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt+|be|ку́рыца|f}}\n* Bengali: {{tt+|bn|মুরগি}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{tt|bcl|gunakan}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|коко́шка|f}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|ကြက်မ}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|gallina|f}}\n* Cebuano: {{t|ceb|himungaan}}\n* Chamicuro: {{tt|ccc|atawali}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|котам}}\n* Cherokee: {{tt|chr|ᏣᏔᎦ ᎠᎩᏏ}}\n* Chin:\n*: Tedim Chin: {{tt|ctd|aak}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|雞乸|tr=gai1 naa2}}, {{tt|yue|母雞|tr=mou5 gai1}} {{q|formal}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt+|nan-hbl|雞母|tr=ke-bú}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|母雞|tr=mǔjī}}\n* Chuvash: {{tt|cv|чӑх}}\n* Coptic: {{tt|cop|ⲁⲛⲁⲡⲁⲓ|f}}\n* Corsican: {{tt+|co|gallina|f}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|slepice|f}}\n* Dalmatian: {{tt|dlm|galaina|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|høne|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|hen|f}}, {{tt+|nl|kip|f}}, {{tt+|nl|leghen|f}}, {{tt+|nl|legkip|f}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt|eo|kokino}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|kana}}\n* Ewe: {{tt|ee|koklonɔ|f}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|høna|f}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kana}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|poule|f}}\n* Frisian:\n*: West Frisian: {{tt|fy|hin|f}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|gjaline|f}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|galiña|f}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|ქათამი}}, {{tt|ka|ქათმისა}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Henne|f}}, {{tt+|de|Legehenne|f}}, {{tt+|de|Huhn|n}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|κότα|f}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|תרנגולת|f|tr=tarnególet|alt=תרנגולת / תַּרְנְגֹלֶת}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|मुर्गी|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|tyúk}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|hæna|f}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|hanino}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt|id|ayam betina}}\n* Ingush: {{tt|inh|котам}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-needed|ia}}\n* Irish: {{tt+|ga|cearc|f}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|gallina|f}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|雌鶏|tr=めんどり, mendori}}\n* Kalenjin: {{tt|kln|ngoket}}\n* Kamba: {{tt|kam|nguku}}\n* Kapampangan: {{t|pam|gaindu}}, {{t|pam|gayindu}}\n* Karachay-Balkar: {{tt|krc|тауукъ|tr=tawuq}}\n* Karakhanid: {{tt|xqa|تَقاغُو|tr=taqāɣū}}\n* Kashmiri: {{tt+|ks|کۄکٕر}}\n* Kazakh: {{tt|kk|тауық}}\n* Khakas: {{tt|kjh|таңах}}\n* Khmer: {{tt|km|មាន់ញី}}\n* Kikuyu: {{tt|ki|mwera|c3}}, {{tt|ki|ngoko}}\n* Komi:\n*: Komi-Permyak: {{tt|koi|курӧг}}\n*: Komi-Zyrian: {{tt|kpv|курӧг}}\n* Kongo: {{t|kg|nsusu}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|암탉}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt+|ckb|مِریشک}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|mirîşk}}\n*: Southern Kurdish: {{tt+|sdh|مامِر}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{tt+|ky|тоок}}\n* Lao: {{tt|lo|ໄກ່ແມ່}}\n* Latin: {{tt+|la|gallīna|f}}\n* Latvian: {{tt+|lv|vista|f}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt+|lt|višta|f}}\n* Low German:\n*: German Low German: {{tt|nds-de|Heen|f}}, {{tt|nds-de|Hään|f}}, {{tt+|nds-de|Hohn|n}}\n* Luhya: {{tt|luy|engokho}}\n* Luo: {{tt|luo|gweno}}\n* Lutuv: {{t|clt|aapuvnung}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt+|mk|ко́кошка|f}}\n* Malay: {{tt|ms|ayam betina}}\n* Maltese: {{tt|mt|tiġieġ|f}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᡝᠮᡳᠯᡝ ᠴᠣᡴᠣ}}\n* Mapudungun: {{tt|arn|achao}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|कोंबडी|f}}\n* Mazanderani: {{tt|mzn|کرک|tr=kərk}}\n* Megleno-Romanian: {{t|ruq|găľină|f}}\n* Meru: {{tt|mer|nguku}}\n* Mi'kmaq: {{tt|mic|go'qoli'gwej|an}}\n* Mòcheno: {{tt|mhn|henn|f}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|mn|[[эм]] [[тахиа]]}}, {{tt+|mn|тахиа}}\n* Naga:\n*: Khiamniungan Naga: {{t|kix|vēunyū}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|gallina|f}}\n* Nivkh: {{tt|niv|пʼеӄ}}\n* Norman: {{tt|nrf|poule|f}} {{q|Jersey}}, {{tt|nrf|g'linne|f}} {{q|Jersey}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt+|nb|høne|m|f}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{tt|nn|høne|f}}\n* Occitan: {{tt+|oc|galina|f}}\n* Old English: {{tt|ang|henn|f}}, {{tt|ang|hænn|f}}\n* Old Prussian: {{t|prg|gerto|f}}\n* Ossetian: {{tt|os|карк}}\n* Papiamentu: {{t|pap|galiña}}\n* Pashto: {{tt|ps|چرګه|f|tr=čǝrga}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|مرغ|tr=morġ}}, {{tt+|fa|کرک|tr=kark}}\n* Pirahã: {{t|myp|páxaihi}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{tt|pdt|Han|f}}\n* Polish: {{tt+|pl|kura|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|galinha|f}}\n* Punjabi: {{tt|pa|کُکَّڑی|f}}\n* Quechua: {{tt+|qu|wallpa}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|găină}}\n* Romansh: {{tt|rm|giaglina}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|ку́рица|f}}\n* Sami:\n*: Southern Sami: {{tt|sma|vöönhtse}}\n* Sardinian: {{tt|sc|pudha|f}}, {{tt|sc|pudda|f}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|cearc|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|ко̀ко̄шка|f}}, {{tt|sh|ко̏ко̄ш|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|kòkōška|f}}, {{tt+|sh|kȍkōš|f}}\n* Sicilian: {{tt+|scn|gaddina}}\n* Slovak: {{tt+|sk|kurča|f}}, {{tt+|sk|sliepka}}\n* Slovene: {{tt+|sl|kokoš|f}}, {{tt+|sl|kura|f}}, {{tt|sl|koklja|f}} {{q|[[broody]] hen}}\n* Sogdian: {{tt|sog|ܡܪܮ|tr=mərγ}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|gallina|f}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|tembe}}, {{tt+|sw|kuku}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|höna|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{tt+|tl|inahin|f}} {{q|literally}}\n* Tajik: {{tt|tg|мурғ}}\n* Talysh: {{t|tly|kağ}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|கோழி}}\n* Taos: {{tt|twf|lìlúna}}\n* Tarifit: {{t|rif|tyaẓiṭ|f}}\n* Tashelhit: {{tt|shi|tafullust|f}}, {{tt|shi|tacicawt|f}}\n* Tat: {{t|ttt|kərg}}\n* Tatar: {{tt+|tt|тавык}}\n* Tày: {{t|tyz|cáy me̱}}\n* Telugu: {{tt+|te|కోడిపెట్ట}}\n* Thai: {{tt|th|แม่ไก่}}\n* Tibetan: {{tt|bo|བྱ་མོ}}\n* Turkish: {{tt+|tr|tavuk}}, {{tt+|tr|bulli}} {{q|Cypriot}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{tt|ota|طاوق|tr=tavuk}}\n* Turkmen: {{tt|tk|towuk}}\n* Udi: {{tt|udi|кӏокӏоц́}}\n* Udmurt: {{tt|udm|курег}}\n* Ukrainian: {{tt+|uk|ку́рка|f}}\n* Urdu: {{tt|ur|مرغی|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{tt|ug|مېكىيان}}\n* Uzbek: {{tt+|uz|tovuq}}\n* Venetan: {{tt|vec|galina|f}}, {{tt+|vec|gaƚina|f}}, {{tt+|vec|pita|f}}\n* Vietnamese: {{tt+|vi|gà mái}}\n* Volapük: {{tt+|vo|jigok}}, {{tt|vo|nögamajigok}} {{q|cf. [[nögön]]}}\n* Walloon: {{tt+|wa|poye|f}}, {{tt+|wa|glene|f}}\n* Welsh: {{tt+|cy|iâr|f}}\n* Wolof: {{tt|wo|ganaar gu jigéen}}\n* Xârâcùù: {{t|ane|dö}}\n* Yakut: {{tt|sah|куурусса}}\n* Zande: {{t|zne|kondo}}\n* Zazaki: {{tt+|zza|kerg}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|female bird}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|մարի}}\n* Avestan: {{t-check|ae|tr=kahrkäsah}}{{attention|ae|Doesn't appear to be a valid transliteration}}\n* Catalan: {{tt|ca|[[au]] [[femella]]|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|母雞|tr=mǔjī}}\n* Corsican: {{tt+|co|gallina}}, {{tt+|co|ghjallina|f}}, {{tt+|co|ghjaddina|f}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|slepice|f}}\n* Dalmatian: {{tt|dlm|čauca}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|høne|c}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|wijfje|n}}, {{tt+|nl|hen|f}}\n* Eshtehardi: {{tt|esh|کرگه|tr=karga}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt|eo|birdino}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|kana}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Weibchen|n}} {{q|generic term for the female of any animal}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|πουλάδα|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|tojó|s}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|gallina}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|めんどり|tr=mendori}}, {{tt+|ja|雌鶏|tr=めんどり, mendori}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|же́нка|f}}\n* Malay: {{tt|ms|ayam betina}}\n* Māori: {{tt|mi|kātua}}, {{tt+|mi|uha}}, {{tt|mi|uwha}}\n* Old English: {{tt|ang|cwēnfugol|m}}\n* Parthian: {{tt|xpr|karga|tr=kirga}}\n* Persian: {{tt+|fa|مرغ|tr=morġ}}\n*: Middle Persian: {{tt|pal|kirk}}\n*: Old Persian: {{tt|peo|tr=karkah}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt|pt|[[ave]]-[[fêmea]]|f}}, {{tt+|pt|pássara|f}}\n* Punjabi: {{t|pa|ਕੁੱਕੜੀ|f}}\n* Quechua: {{tt|qu|tuqtu}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|ку́рочка|f}}, {{tt+|ru|са́мка|f}} {{q|zoology, female of animals, cf. {{l|ru|саме́ц}}}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|cearc|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|женка|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|ženka|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt|es|[[ave]] [[hembra]]|f}}\n* Swahili: {{tt+|sw|tembe}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|höna|c}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|பெண்}}\n* Telugu: {{tt|te|ఆడపక్షి}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|xkwehële}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|female fish|spawner}}\n\n{{trans-top|hen-like woman}}\n{{multitrans|data=\n* Dutch: {{tt|nl|moederkloek|f}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|poule|f}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|κότα|f}} {{q|pejorative}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|gallina}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt+|mk|ко́кошка|f}} {{q|pejorative}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|galinha|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|тёлка|f}} {{q|slang, pejorative}}, {{tt+|ru|ба́ба|f}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt|sh|кока|f}}\n*: Latin: {{tt+|sh|koka|f}}\n* Swedish: {{tt+|sv|brud}}, {{tt+|sv|brutta}}\n* Tamil: {{tt+|ta|பெண்}}\n}}<!-- close {{multitrans}} -->\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|intransitive}} {{synonym of|en|mother-hen}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en |year=1943|title=McCall's - Volume 71 |author=|page=69|ISBN=|passage=Once he had flared up, \"If ever a man was '''henned''', it's me!\" }}\n#* {{quote-book|en |year=1984|title=Love Beyond Surrender |author=Susan C. Feldhake |page=52|ISBN=|passage=Mammy '''henned''' the black workers into placing the trunks beside the girls.}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|en|broody}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|henne}}, {{m|enm|heonne}}, {{m|enm|hinne}}, from earlier {{m|enm|henene}}, {{m|enm|heonenen}}, {{m|enm|henen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|heonan}}, {{m|ang|hionan}}, {{m|ang|heonane}}, {{m|ang|heonone||hence, from here, away, from how}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hina}}, {{m|gem-pro|*hinanō||from here}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*ḱe-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*ḱey-||this, here}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|heen||away}}, {{cog|de|hin||hence, from here}}, {{cog|da|hen||away, further, on}}. See also {{l|en|hence}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|dialectal}} [[hence|Hence]].\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{m|en|hen||hence, away}}, or a variant of {{m|en|hench}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|dialectal}} To [[throw]].\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Fielding 2021|page=96}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=ehn|NHE|Neh.}}\n\n{{c|en|Birds|Chickens|Female animals|Venerida order mollusks|Genitalia}}\n\n==Breton==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|br|cel-bry-pro|*hen}}, from {{inh|br|cel-pro|*senos}}, from {{inh|br|ine-pro|*sénos}}.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|br|adjective}}\n\n# [[old]], [[ancient]]\n\n==Cimbrian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|cim|haban|håm}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|cim|gmh|haben}}, from {{inh|cim|goh|hāben}}, from {{inh|cim|gmw-pro|*habbjan}}, from {{inh|cim|gem-pro|*habjaną||to have; to hold}}. Cognate with {{cog|de|haben}}, {{cog|en|have}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|cim|verb|[[Appendix:Glossary#irregular|irregular]]||auxiliary|hen|cat2=irregular verbs}}\n\n# {{lb|cim|Thirteen Communities}} to [[have]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Patuzzi}}\n\n==Cornish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|kw|cel-bry-pro|*hen}}, from {{inh|kw|cel-pro|*senos}}.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{head|kw|adjective}}\n\n# {{lb|kw|archaic}} [[old]]\n# [[long-standing]]\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|da|gml|hen}}, ultimately related to {{der|da|gem-pro|*hiz|t=here}}. Related to {{cog|sv|hän}}, {{cog|en|hence}}, and {{cog|de|hin}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈhɛn]|[ˈhɛnˀ]}}\n* {{rhymes|da|ɛn|s=1}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{da-adv}}\n\n# {{ng|Used with a verb, indicating a movement towards or to something.}} <!-- This could be elaborated greatly. Confer with Norwegian entries.-->\n#: Gå '''hen''' til din far.\n#:: Go to your father.\n#: Hestene går '''hen''' imod mig.\n#:: The horses are walking towards me.\n\n====Usage notes====\nContrast with ''{{l|da|henne}}''; where ''hen'' indicates movement, ''henne'' indicates position. Thus ''hvor løber han henne?'' means \"where is he running?\", whereas ''hvor løber han hen?'' means \"to where is he running?\".\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/ɦɛn/}}\n* {{hyphenation|nl|hen}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɛn|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|nl|odt|hin}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*himaz}}.\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|nl|pronoun|personal}}\n\n# [[them]]; {{ng|third-person plural objective personal pronoun}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* See the usage notes at {{m|nl|hun}} for details on use.\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{nl-personal pronouns}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|nl\n|henzelf\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|nl\n|hun\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|nl|dum|henne}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*henna}}, from {{inh|nl|gmw-pro|*hannju}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*hanjō}}, from {{der|nl|ine-pro|*keh₂n-||to sing}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nl-noun|f|-en|+|m=haan}}\n\n# {{senseid|nl|chicken}} {{l|en|hen}}, female [[chicken]]; female of a related species\n# a female of the species of birds [[brood]]ing on the ground\n# {{lb|nl|figuratively}} 'bird', colloquial term for a human female\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* (female chicken) {{l|nl|kip}}, {{l|nl|kieken}}\n* (brooding bird) {{l|nl|kloek}}\n* (female human; informal) {{l|nl|kippetje}}, {{l|nl|duifje}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|nl|haan|g=m}} (rooster)\n* {{l|nl|hoen}}, {{l|nl|hoender|g=n}} (fowl)\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|af|hen}}\n* {{desc|gmw-jdt|hän}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nChosen in an online poll by {{lw|nl|Transgender Netwerk Nederland}} in 2016. The alternative {{m|nl|die}} arose from the same poll.<ref>{{cite-web|nl|date=20 June 2016|work=Onze Taal|url=https://onzetaal.nl/nieuws-en-dossiers/taalnieuws/transgender-netwerk-kiest-geslachtloze-voornaamwoorden|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20201017202601/https://onzetaal.nl/nieuws-en-dossiers/taalnieuws/transgender-netwerk-kiest-geslachtloze-voornaamwoorden}}</ref>\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|nl|pronoun|possessive|hun}}\n\n# {{lb|nl|gender-neutral|nonstandard}} {{ng|A [[gender-neutral]] singular third-person personal pronoun.}}\n## {{l|en|they|id=third-person singular nominative}} {{qualifier|singular}} {{ng|subject pronoun}}\n## [[them]] {{qualifier|singular}} {{ng|object pronoun}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nUnlike English {{w|Singular they|singular ''they''}}, Dutch gender-neutral ''hen'' agrees with a verb in singular:\n: {{uxi|nl|'''Hen''' is '''hun''' portemonnee kwijt.|'''They''' have lost '''their''' wallet.}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|gender-neutral 3sg pronoun}} {{m|nl|die}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{pedia|lang=nl|Genderneutrale voornaamwoorden#Nederlands}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n{{C|nl|Chickens|Female animals}}\n\n==Finnish==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|fi|noun form}}\n\n# {{infl of|fi|he||gen|s|t=he (a letter of some Semitic alphabets)|id=letter}}\n\n==Japanese==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{ja-romaji}}\n\n# {{ja-romanization of|へん}}\n\n==Mandarin==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{cmn-pinyin|notr=1}}\n\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|hēn}}\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|hén}}\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|hěn}}\n# {{nonstandard spelling of|cmn|sc=Latn|hèn}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{cmn-toneless-note}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|enm|henne|hene|han|en|heene}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|enm|gmw-pro|gem-pro|inh=2}}\nFrom {{inh|enm|ang|henn}}, from {{inh|enm|gmw-pro|*hannju}}, from {{inh|enm|gem-pro|*hanjō}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|enm|/hɛn/}}\n* {{rhymes|enm|ɛn|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{enm-noun|gen=hennes|gen2=henne|pl=hennes|pl2=hennen}}\n\n# {{l|en|hen}}, [[chicken]]\n# [[female]] [[bird]]\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|en|hen}}\n* {{desc|sco|hen}}\n* {{desc|yol|hen|alts=1}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=hen |pos=n.(1) |id= MED20374 |accessdate=2018-04-03}}\n\n{{c|enm|Birds|Chickens|Female animals}}\n\n==Mohawk==\n\n===Particle===\n{{head|moh|particle}}\n\n# [[yes]]\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|nb|gml|hen}}, {{m|gml|henne}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{nb-adv}}\n\n# {{ng|used with a verb, indicating a movement towards or to something.}} <!-- This could be elaborated greatly. Confer with Danish entry.-->\n# {{lb|nb|dialectal}} [[where]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{wp|+ (pronoun)}}\nThrough {{bor|nb|sv|hen}} from {{der|nb|fi|hän}}.\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|nb|pronoun|{{m|en|third person}} {{m|en|singular}} {{m|en|gender-neutral}} {{m|en|personal pronoun}}||{{m|en|possessive}}|hens}}\n\n# [[they]]\n#: {{ux|nb|Hvis noen kjører over fartsgrensen, må '''hen''' betale en bot.|t=If someone exceeds the speed limit, '''they''' must pay a fine.}}\n#: {{ux|nb|Kommer studenten for sent, må '''hen''' vente ute.|If the student comes too late, '''they''' have to wait outside.}}\n#: {{ux|nb|Har du nummeret '''hens'''?|Do you have '''their''' number?}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* ''Hen'' can be used when someone's gender is unknown or irrelevant, or to refer to someone who prefers a gender neutral pronoun instead of {{m|nb|han||he}} or {{m|nb|hun||she}}.\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|nb|han||he}}, {{l|nb|hun||she}}, {{l|nb|vedkommende||they}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb:OB}}\n* {{R:nb:NAOB|hen_2}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://www.sprakradet.no/svardatabase/sporsmal-og-svar/hen/ \"Det kjønnsnøytrale pronomenet hen har kome inn i norsk dei siste åra og blir brukt i to litt ulike tydingar. I juni 2022 kom ordet òg inn i rettskrivingsnormene for nynorsk og bokmål.\"]\n* “[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/feb/02/new-gender-neutral-pronoun-norwegian-dictionaries-hen-official-language New gender-neutral pronoun likely to enter Norwegian dictionaries]” by Weronika Strzyżyńska (2022-02-02), in ''{{w|The Guardian}}''\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{der|nn|gml|hen}}, {{m|gml|henne}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{nn-adv}}\n\n# {{ng|used with a verb, indicating a movement towards or to something.}} <!-- This could be elaborated greatly. Confer with Danish entry.-->\n# {{lb|nn|dialectal}} [[where]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{wp|+ (pronoun)}}\nThrough {{bor|nn|sv|hen}} from {{der|nn|fi|hän}}.\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|nn|pronoun|{{m|en|third person}} {{m|en|singular}} {{m|en|gender-neutral}} {{m|en|personal pronoun}}||{{m|en|possessive}}|hens}}\n\n# [[they]]\n#: {{ux|nn|Kjem studenten for seint, må '''hen''' venta ute.|If the student comes too late, '''they''' have to wait outside.}}\n#: {{ux|nn|Har du nummeret '''hens'''?|Do you have '''their''' number?}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* ''Hen'' can be used when someone's gender is unknown or irrelevant, or to refer to someone who prefers a gender neutral pronoun instead of {{m|nn|han||he}} or {{m|nn|ho||she}}.\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|nn|han||he}}, {{l|nn|ho||she}}, {{l|nn|vedkomande||they}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n* {{cite-book|nn|year=2005|entry=hen|title=Norsk ordbok: ordbok over det norske folkemålet og det nynorske skriftmålet|volume=5|location=Oslo|publisher=Samlaget|columns=292–293}}\n* {{R:no:Aasen}}\n* {{R:nb:NAOB|hen_2}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* “[https://www.sprakradet.no/svardatabase/sporsmal-og-svar/hen/ Det kjønnsnøytrale pronomenet hen har kome inn i norsk dei siste åra og blir brukt i to litt ulike tydingar]”\n* “[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/feb/02/new-gender-neutral-pronoun-norwegian-dictionaries-hen-official-language New gender-neutral pronoun likely to enter Norwegian dictionaries]” by Weronika Strzyżyńska (2022-02-02), in ''{{w|The Guardian}}''\n\n==Polish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|pl|heń||Southern Greater Poland}}\n* {{alt|pl|hań||Kielce|Przemyśl|Żywiec|Western Lublin|Eastern Lublin|Lublin Voivodeship|Zamość County}}\n* {{alt|pl|haj||Kielce}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|pl|:inh|sla-pro:*eno|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|a=LL-Q809 (pol)-Olaf-hen.wav}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{pl-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|literary}} [[far away]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:WSJP}}\n* {{R:pl:PWN}}\n\n{{cln|pl|location adverbs}}\n\n==Scots==\n\n===Noun===\n{{sco-noun|-}}\n\n# Term of address for a [[woman]].\n#: {{ux|sco|Alright Mary '''hen'''?}}\n\n==Swedish==\n{{wp|+ (pronoun)}}\n{{was fwotd|sv|2013|March|11}}\n[[File:Hen - The Swedish pronoun.svg|thumb|alt=A unified femininity and masculinity symbol with “hen” in the center|“Hen” represented among other personal pronouns in Swedish]]\n\n===Etymology 1===\nCreated as an alternative to {{m|sv|hon|t=she}} and {{m|sv|han|t=he}}. The coining of the word has probably been influenced by the Finnish {{m|fi|hän}}, a personal pronoun used about human beings and which does not specify gender (Finnish lacks grammatical gender entirely). ''Hen'' was suggested as early as 1966 by linguist {{coinage|sv|Rolf Dunås|w=sv|notext=1|nobycat=1}} in Swedish regional newspaper ''{{w|Upsala Nya Tidning}}'' and was proposed again in a 1994 article by linguist Hans Karlgren, but did not receive widespread attention until around 2010.<ref>{{cite-journal|date=8 March 2012|author=Anders Q Björkman|title=”Hen” föreslogs av språkforskare redan 1994 – i SvD|trans-title=”Hen” proposed by linguists already 1994 – in SvD|journal={{w|Svenska Dagbladet}}|url=http://blog.svd.se/kultur/2012/03/08/%E2%80%9Dhen%E2%80%9D-foreslogs-av-sprakforskare-redan-1994-%E2%80%93-i-svd|accessdate=7 January 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820042551/http://blog.svd.se/kultur/2012/03/08/%E2%80%9Dhen%E2%80%9D-foreslogs-av-sprakforskare-redan-1994-%E2%80%93-i-svd/|archivedate=10 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|sv|/hɛn/}}\n* {{audio|sv|sv-hen.ogg|a=Central Standard Swedish}}\n* {{rhymes|sv|ɛn}}\n* {{rhymes|sv|ɛnː|s=1}}\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|sv|pronoun|{{m|en|third person}} {{m|en|singular}} {{m|en|gender-neutral}} {{m|en|personal pronoun}}||{{m|en|oblique}}|hen|or|henom|{{m|en|possessive}}|hens}}\n\n# {{n-g|A third-person singular pronoun of unspecified gender;}} [[they]], [[thon]]; {{n-g|alternative to {{m|sv|hon||she}} and {{m|sv|han||he}}.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|sv|year=2011|author=Anders Lokko |title=En sång om att ha följt sitt hjärta |journal=w:Svenska Dagbladet |url=http://www.svd.se/kultur/en-sang-om-att-ha-foljt-sitt-hjarta_6913451.svd |text=Alla skilsmässor och separationer är olika. Men i nästan samtliga är det i slutändan någon som blir lämnad och någon som lämnar. Ingen av de rollerna är enkel. Fast det är när den som lämnar gör det för att '''hen''' har träffat någon annan […] |t=All divorces and separations are different. But in almost all cases, someone is left behind or someone leaves. None of those roles are easy. However, it's when the one who does leaves because '''they''' have met someone else […]}}\n#* {{quote-journal |sv |year=2011 |author=Lotten Wiklund |title=Jag vill vara hen – inte hon eller han |journal=w:Dagens Nyheter |url=http://www.dn.se/insidan/insidan-hem/jag-vill-vara-hen--inte-hon-eller-han |text=I efterhand har '''hen''' förstått att det förmodligen har att göra med att '''hen''' aldrig riktigt accepterat att det bara skulle finnas två kön. |t=In hindsight, '''they''' have come to understand that it probably has to do with the fact that '''they''' have never accepted that there are just two genders. |accessdate=7 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602213303/http://www.dn.se/insidan/insidan-hem/jag-vill-vara-hen--inte-hon-eller-han |archivedate=2 June 2013 }}\n#* {{quote-book|sv|year=2012|author=Jesper Lundqvist|title=Kivi och Monsterhund |text=[…]ska '''hen''' få en hund, kan de halvt säkert lova[…]|t=[…]then '''they''' will get a dog, they can almost promise[…]}}\n#* {{quote-journal|sv|year=2013 |author=Lova Olsson |title=Arnholm lanserar 'hen' i riksdagen |journal=w:Svenska Dagbladet |url=http://www.svd.se/nyheter/inrikes/arnholm-lanserar-hen-i-riksdagen_7911126.svd |text=– Målet är att varje individ ska få det stöd '''hen''' behöver för att så snabbt som möjligt lära sig svenska, komma i arbete och klara sin egen försörjning, sade den nyblivna jämställdhetsministern. |t=– The goal is to make sure that every individual should receive the support '''they''' need to learn Swedish, start working and manage to support themselves as soon as possible, said the newly appointed Minister of Gender Equality.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|sv|year=2013 |author=Ann-Marie Begler; Caroline Dyrefors Grufman |title=Flera allvarliga kränkningar i skolan de senaste veckorna |journal=w:Dagens Nyheter |url=http://www.dn.se/debatt/flera-allvarliga-krankningar-i-skolan-de-senaste-veckorna/ |text=– En person i personalen som sliter i och skäller på barnen, hotar med stryk och skrämmer dem med det '''hen''' vet att de är rädda för. |t=– A person on the staff pushes around and yells at the children, threatens with violence and frightens them with things '''they''' know they are afraid of.}}\n#* {{quote-book|sv|year=2014 |author=Nina Åkestam |title=Meningen med hela skiten |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxffBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PT126&dq=%22hen%22%20sverige%20%22och%22&pg=PT50#v=snippet&q=%22Vill%20hen%20att%20du%20ska%20chansa,%20eller%20ta%20det%20lugnt?%22&f=false |text=Vill '''hen''' att du ska chansa, eller ta det lugnt? |t=Do '''they''' want you to gamble or to take it easy?}}\n#* {{quote-book|sv|year=2015 |author=Ami Sundeman; Anna Lytsy |title=Kosmosdialogerna |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5gLbCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT237&dq=%22och%20hen%22%20sverige&pg=PT5#v=onepage&q=%22hens%22&f=false |text='''Hens''' utgångspunkt är alltid större och mera allomfattande än så. |t='''Their''' starting point is always greater and more all-encompassing than that.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* Although the word has gained common use, it is not nearly as common as the gendered words ''han'' and ''hon''. From 2011 to 2020, usage of ''hen'' increased hundredfold in the media, but no increase was seen in 2021.<ref>{{cite-web|date=18 January 2022 |title=Hen står still i svenska medier |trans-title=''hen'' is stagnant in Swedish media|titleurl=https://spraktidningen.se/2022/01/hen-star-still-i-svenska-medier/|publisher=Språktidningen |work=Språktidningen |accessdate=18 January 2022}}</ref> It has been especially popular among activists for gender equality and adherents of {{w|queer theory}}, and with the transgender community.<ref>{{cite-journal|date=17 May 2011 |title=”Jag vill vara hen – inte hon eller han” |trans-title=”I want to be ''hen'' – not ''hon'' or ''han''” |journal={{w|Dagens Nyheter}} |url=http://www.dn.se/insidan/jag-vill-vara-hen-inte-hon-eller-han/}}</ref> In 2022, usage of ''hen'' was ranked in shared first place alongside misspelling of words as the most annoying language phenomenon in a Swedish survey.<ref>{{cite-web|date=25 April 2022 |title=Särskrivningar och hen irriterar mest i svenskan |trans-title=Splitting of compound words and hen causing most irritation in Swedish |url=https://spraktidningen.se/2022/04/spraket-som-stor-mest/|publisher=Språktidningen |work=Språktidningen |accessdate=26 January 2023}}</ref> Publishers of manuals of style and the {{w|Swedish Language Council}} do not proscribe the usage of ''hen'', but recommend the inflected forms ''hens'' as the possessive and ''hen'' over ''henom'' as the object.<ref>{{R:svenska.se|saol}}</ref><ref>{{cite-web|date=25 August 2014|title=Hur använder man pronomenet hen?|trans-title=How is the pronoun ''hen'' used?|titleurl=http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/sprak/sprakradgivning/aktuellt-sprakrad/granskade-rad/2014-04-30-hur-anvander-man-pronomenet-hen.html|work=Aktuellt språkråd|publisher={{w|Swedish Language Council}}|accessdate=12 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150529135120/http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/sprak/sprakradgivning/aktuellt-sprakrad/granskade-rad/2014-04-30-hur-anvander-man-pronomenet-hen.html|archivedate=29 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{sv-personal pronouns}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sv|vederbörande}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|sv|non|hein}}, from {{inh|sv|gem-pro|*hainō}}.\n\nRelated to Norwegian and {{cog|is|hein|t=whetstone}}, {{cog|ang|han|hān|t=stone, rock}} and modern {{cog|en|hone}}. Further related to {{cog|sa|शाण}} and {{cog|la|cos|cōs}} with the same meaning. See also (dialectal) Swedish {{m|sv|hena|t=to hone}}.<ref>{{R:svenska.se|saob}}</ref>\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|sv|/heːn/}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{sv-noun|c}}\n\n# {{lb|sv|archaic|dialectal}} a [[whetstone]], particularly the small and soft kind.\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{sv-infl-noun-c-ar|hen|hen}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|sv|bryne|g=n}}\n* {{l|sv|brynsten|g=c}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|sv|slipsten|g=c|t=grindstone}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Veps==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|vep|urj-fin-pro|*hëëno}}. Cognates include {{cog|fi|hieno}}.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{vep-adj}}\n\n# [[fine]]\n# [[refined]], [[elegant]]\n\n====Inflection====\n{{vep-decl-ilo|heno}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|vep|henota}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:vep:UVVV|изысканный|мелкий|тонкий|утончённый}}\n\n==Vietnamese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{vi-IPA}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nCognate with {{cog|kdt|-}} [Salavan] ''hɛːn'' (\"to cough\").\n\n====Noun====\n{{vi-noun|[[𠻃]], [[𤹖]]}}\n\n# {{lb|vi|disease}} {{lang|vi|([[bệnh]] ~)}} [[asthma]]\n#: {{syn|vi|suyễn|hen suyễn}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|vi|ho hen|hen suyễn}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{vi-verb|[[𠻃]], [[𤹖]]}}\n\n# {{lb|vi|North Central Vietnam}} to [[cough]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Particle====\n{{vi-particle}}\n\n# {{lb|vi|Southern Vietnam}} [[okay]]?; [[alright]]?\n\n==Welsh==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|cy|cel-bry-pro|*hen}}, from {{inh|cy|cel-pro|*senos}}, from {{inh|cy|ine-pro|*sénos}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/heːn/}}\n* {{rhymes|cy|eːn|s=1}}\n* {{rhymes|cy|ɛn|s=1}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{cy-adj|ach|pl=henion|eq=hyned|comp=hŷn|comp2=hynach|comp3=henach|sup=hynaf|sup2=henaf}}\n\n# [[old]], [[aged]]; [[ancient]], [[antique]], [[pristine]], [[former]]; [[inveterate]], [[chronic]]; [[original]]; [[senior]], [[elder]]\n#: {{antonyms|cy|ifanc|ieuanc|newydd}}\n# [[stale]], [[mouldy]], [[musty]], [[fusty]]\n# [[unreformed]], old, [[traditional]] (of style or mode of expressing dates according to the Julian Calendar); reckoned according to the Old Style (of festival)\n\n====Usage notes====\n* This adjective has an alternate, more “senior” comparative in the form of {{m|cy|hŷn}} and an equivalent alternate superlative in the form of {{m|cy|hynaf}}.\n* Unlike most Welsh adjectives, this word goes before the noun.\n* Like most Welsh adjectives that go before the noun, this word triggers a [[soft mutation]] in the word that follows it.\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|cy\n|Hen Gymraeg<t:Old Welsh>\n|Hen Aifft<t:Ancient Egypt>\n|Hen Roeg<t:Ancient Greek>\n|hen Rufain<t:Ancient Rome>\n|hen wlad Groeg<t:Ancient Greece>\n|Hen Wlad fy Nhadau<pos:Welsh national anthem>\n|henwlad<t:old country, Wales>\n|hen bryd<t:about time>\n|henaint<t:old age>\n|hen sguthan<t:horrible woman>\n|hen bobl<t:old people, the elderly>\n|hen daid<t:great grandfather>\n|hen dad-cu<t:great grandfather>\n|hen fam-gu<t:great grandmother>\n|hen nain<t:great grandmother>\n|hen law<t:old hand>\n|hen ffasiwn<t:old-fashioned, dated>\n|hen gnawes<t:old shrew>\n|hen jaden<t:horrible woman>\n|hen lanc<t:bachelor>\n|hen nodiant<t:staff notation>\n|henadur<t:elder; alderman>\n|hendref<t:winter dwelling>\n|heneb<t:ancient monument>\n|heneiddio<t:to age>\n|heniaith<t:ancient language, Welsh>\n|henoed<t:old age>\n|henwr<t:old man>\n|henaidd<t:oldish, quaint>\n|henuriad<t:elder>\n|hen a methedig<t:old and infirm>\n|Hen Ddihenydd<t:Ancient of Days>\n|Hen Destament<t:Old Testament>\n|hen ferch<t:spinster, old maid>\n|[[Hen Fyd|yr Hen Fyd]]<t:the Old World>\n|hen gono<t:old fogey>\n|Hen Gynghrair<t:Auld Alliance>\n|hen groc<t:old crock>\n|Hen Norseg<t:Old Norse>\n|Hen Saesneg<t:Old English>\n|Hen Wyddeleg<t:Old Irish>\n|Hen Ffrangeg<t:Old French>\n|hen geg<t:babbler>\n|hen bennill<t:stanza of folk poetry>\n|barf yr hen ŵr<t:traveller‘s-joy, {{taxfmt|Clematis vitalba|species}}>\n|mor hen â phechod<t:as old as sin>\n|cyn hyned â phechod<t:as old as sin>\n|yr hen a ŵyr, yr ifanc a dybia<t:the old know, the young think they know>\n|henach henach, ffolach ffolach<t:there's no fool like an old fool>\n|[[Henfyd|yr Henfyd]]<t:the Ancient World>\n|Hen Oes y Cerrig<t:Old Stone Age, Palaeolithic>\n|Hen Gredadun<t:Old Believer>\n|hen ddyn<t:old man, old Adam>\n|Hen Feili<t:Old Bailey>\n|Hen Ogledd<t:Old North (Brittonic southern Scotland and northern England)>\n|hawdd cynnau tân ar hen aelwyd<t:it is easy to rekindle love with an old flame>\n|Henffordd<t:Hereford>\n|Hendy-gwyn ar Daf<t:Whitland>\n|hen beth<t:antique>\n|hen ddigon<t:quite enough>\n|hendraul<t:threadbare>\n|hen dro<t:pity, shame>\n}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|yol|hin}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|hen}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|henn}}, from {{inh|yol|gmw-pro|*hannju}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/hɛn/|/hɪn/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|yol|noun|plural|henès}}\n\n# {{l|en|hen}}\n#: {{cot|yol|cuck}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=CASTEALE CUDDE'S LAMENTATION|number=4|page=104|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Hea pryet ich mought na ha chicke or '''hen''',|translation=He prayed I might not have chicken nor '''hen''',}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=46}}\n\n{{C|yol|Poultry}}"}}